{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536866"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:10:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:10:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15826"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15826"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.14,0.47,0.11,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8517"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102762"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8517"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15826"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85245"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1095"},{"type":"tags","id":"1154"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"9051"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20443"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34652"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43594"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102762"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 44-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of worsening back and shoulder pain. He has a medical history of ankylosing spondylitis diagnosed 10 years ago, anterior uveitis, and inflammatory bowel disease. He does not take any regular medications. He works as an accountant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable but well. His pulse rate is 76/min, blood pressure 128/82 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. There is reduced range of movement in his cervical and thoracolumbar spine with tenderness on palpation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prednisolone","Physiotherapy","Naproxen","Paracetamol","Adalimumab"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with an acute flare of ankylosing spondylitis (AS), characterised by worsening axial pain and reduced spinal mobility. The presence of anterior uveitis and inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) is consistent with the extra-articular manifestations commonly seen in AS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENaproxen\u003C/strong\u003E or another NSAID is the most appropriate first-line treatment for acute flares of AS. NSAIDs effectively reduce inflammation and provide pain relief by inhibiting prostaglandin synthesis. Gastrointestinal side effects of NSAIDs can be mitigated by consideration of concurrent proton pump inhibitor therapy. NSAIDs should be trialled at the maximum tolerated dose for 2-4 weeks before being considered ineffective.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhysiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E, while important in the long-term management of AS to maintain spinal mobility and prevent deformity, is not sufficient as initial therapy during an acute inflammatory flare. However, patients should be encouraged to continue gentle exercise and stretching even during flares.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E has a limited role in AS management. While systemic corticosteroids may occasionally be used for peripheral arthritis or severe extra-articular manifestations, they are not recommended for axial disease due to limited evidence of benefit and significant long-term side effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacetamol\u003C/strong\u003E alone is inadequate for managing inflammatory pain in AS. While it may be used as an adjunct analgesic, it does not address the underlying inflammation that characterises an acute flare.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdalimumab\u003C/strong\u003E and other biological agents are reserved for patients with active disease who have failed an adequate trial of at least two different NSAIDs over a four-week period. They require careful patient selection, screening, and monitoring, and are not appropriate as initial therapy for an acute flare.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["NSAIDs are first-line treatment for acute flares of ankylosing spondylitis.","Exercise and physiotherapy should be continued during flares of ankylosing spondylitis to maintain mobility.","Biological agents are reserved for patients who have failed NSAID therapy."],"references":["Ebrahimiadib N, Berijani S, Ghahari M, Pahlaviani FG. Ankylosing Spondylitis. J Ophthalmic Vis Res. 2021 Jul 29;16(3):462-469. doi: 10.18502/jovr.v16i3.9440. PMID: 34394873; PMCID: PMC8358754. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8358754/","Braun J, Sieper J. Ankylosing spondylitis. The Lancet. 2007 Apr 21;369(9570):1379-90. Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/article/S0140-6736(07)60635-7/abstract"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85245"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15826"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85245","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85245"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-15T13:11:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-15T13:11:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8517"}},"content":{"data":{